						<summary>

						<p><hi rend="bold">Parāntaka. Year 15: A.D. 922.</hi></p>						

						<p>The inscription seems to be a copy re-engraved in the 13th century. Records that the <hi rend="italic">Nāṭṭavar</hi> of Ēḻugarait Tiruvāyppāḍi agreed to pay to the deity of Krishṇa (Veṇṇaikkūtta Nāyaṉār) in the temple of Paḷḷikoṇḍāḻvār at Īrōḍu (Erode) certain local taxes levied on the people of the locality to defray the expenses for the supply of sacred food offerings in the temple. The levy was imposed at the rate of half <hi rend="italic">paṇam</hi> on each household <hi rend="italic">(kuḍi)</hi> and one eighth (1/8) <hi rend="italic">paṇam</hi> on each bride and bridegroom. One <hi rend="italic">kuṉṟi</hi> and <hi rend="italic">mañcāṭi</hi> (3/4 <hi rend="italic">kācu</hi>) was levied as <hi rend="italic">cuṭukāṭṭuppāṭṭam</hi> at the place of cremation. </p>						

						<p>Published in <hi rend="italic">S.I.I.</hi>, vol. XXXII, pt. I, No. 20; <hi rend="italic">ERMK.</hi>, Vol. I, No. 1008/2003, p. 27-28.</p>						

						</summary>
